## The Formal Definition of Outside in a Perspective

The most important relationships:
```
(x) =(p)> x =|> x =p> x
(x) =(x)> x =|> {token for being identified}
```

The second relationship is crucial: when something has a canonical symbol that refers to it through itself, this IS the token for being identified. The formalism is subtle here (see: The Semantics of Identity).

A frame is a representation with four essential components:
- **Literature(L)** - The literals being represented (the outside)
- **Catalogue(L)** - The symbols that reference the literals  
- **Composition(L)** - The interacting characters that build symbols
- **Specification(L)** - The rules governing representation

The Literature exists in F[[L]] - the frame of literals, not in the representation frame F[L]. Elements in Literature are what is represented, not the representing machinery. This is dereferencing: accessing the literal content that a representation points to.

```
x =|in> Literature(L) =|> x =|in> F[[L]]
```

The Literature IS the outside of the Catalogue. The symbols in the Catalogue reference the literals in the Literature, but those literals don't inherit from L - they inherit from [L]. They are identified (have symbols) but cannot themselves symbolize.

