## A Theorem about Fundamental Representational Roles

We say that x represents y when:
```
x != y
x =x> y
```

We say that x is a representative of y when:
```
x != y
x =y> y
```

Note that inheritance binds them together:
```
x =x> y & x -> y =|> x =y> y
```

But notice that both expressions are about the relationship between x and y. That there is a most specific relationship is expressed as:
```
x =(x,y)> y
```

In the case where x is a symbol for y:
```
(x,y) == x
```

In the case where x is a canonical of y:
```
(x,y) == y
```

These two cases are mutually exclusive:
```
x =represents> y & x =representative> y =||>
x =symbol> y | x =canonical> y =|>
x =symbol> y || x =canonical> y
```

It's a bit of a weird theorem, because x doesn't have to play either role. But if is to play either, it can't play both!

